{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Afghanistan", "text_new": "{{short description|Ongoing COVID-19 viral pandemic in Afghanistan}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Afghanistan\n| map1            = Afghanistan 2020 COVID-19 Map (Allio-19).png\n| legend1         = Map of provinces with confirmed cases of COVID-19 in Afghanistan '''as of 7 April 2020'''\n{{legend|#c80000|Confirmed cases reported}}\n{{legend|#558eed|Suspected cases reported}}\n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Afghanistan]]\n| first_case      = [[Herat]]\n| arrival_date    = 24 February 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month=02|day=24|year=2020}})\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], [[China]]\n| deaths          = 18\n| recovery_cases  = 32\n| confirmed_cases = 607\n| active_cases    = 474\n| suspected_cases = 2737<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tolonews.com/index.php/health/number-covid-19-cases-afghanistan-367 |title=Number of COVID-19 Cases in Afghanistan: 367 |publisher=TOLOnews |date= |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n| total_ili       = \n| website         = {{url|https://moph.gov.af/dr/\u0634\u06cc\u0648\u0639-\u0648\u06cc\u0631\u0648\u0633-\u06a9\u0631\u0648\u0646\u0627}}\n}}\n\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have spread to [[Afghanistan]] when its [[index case]], in [[Herat]], was confirmed on 24 February 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/asia-pacific/afghanistan-confirms-1st-case-of-coronavirus/1743012|title=Afghanistan confirms 1st case of coronavirus|website=www.aa.com.tr|access-date=2020-03-10}}</ref> \n\nAs of 12 April 2020, there have been 607 positive cases, with 32 recoveries and 18 deaths across 25 provinces in the country. [[Herat Province]] has the highest number of cases at 265 (including 4 deaths), followed by [[Kabul Province]] with 97 cases, and then [[Kandahar Province]] with 32 cases.\n\n== Background ==\nOn 12 January 2020, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) confirmed that a [[novel coronavirus]] was the cause of a respiratory illness in a cluster of people in Wuhan City, Hubei Province, China, which was reported to the WHO on 31 December 2019.<ref name=Elsevier>{{cite web |url=https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center |title=Novel Coronavirus Information Center |last=Elsevier |date= |website=Elsevier Connect|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130171622/https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center|archive-date=30 January 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Reynolds4March2020>{{Cite news |last=Reynolds |first=Matt |url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus |title=What is coronavirus and how close is it to becoming a pandemic? |date=4 March 2020 |work=Wired UK|access-date=5 March 2020 |issn=1357-0978|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305104806/https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus|archive-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Case fatality rate|case fatality ratio]] for COVID-19 has been much lower than [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS of 2003]],<ref name=Imperial13March2020>{{cite web |url= https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/ |title=Crunching the numbers for coronavirus |website=Imperial News|access-date=15 March 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200319084913/https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Gov.ukHCIDDef>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid |title=High consequence infectious diseases (HCID); Guidance and information about high consequence infectious diseases and their management in England |last= |first= |date= |website=GOV.UK |language=en|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200303051938/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid|archive-date=3 March 2020|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> but the [[Transmission (medicine)|transmission]] has been significantly greater, with a significant total death toll.<ref name=WFSA>{{cite web |url= https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus |title=World Federation Of Societies of Anaesthesiologists \u2013 Coronavirus |last= |first= |date= |website=www.wfsahq.org|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200312233527/https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus|archive-date=12 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Imperial13March2020/>\n\n==Timeline==\n{{Main|Timeline of the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Afghanistan}}{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/Afghanistan medical cases chart}}\n\n===February 2020===\nOn 23 February, at least three citizens of [[Herat]] who had recently returned from [[Qom|Qom, Iran]] were suspected of [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19 infection]]. Blood samples were sent to [[Kabul]] for further testing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tolonews.com/afghanistan/3-suspected-cases-coronavirus-reported-afghanistan|title=3 Suspected Cases of Coronavirus Reported in Afghanistan|website=TOLOnews|access-date=23 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 February, [[Afghanistan]] confirmed the first COVID-19 case involving one of the three people from Herat, a 35-year-old man, who tested positive for [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|SARS-CoV-2]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-afghanistan/afghanistan-identifies-first-confirmed-coronavirus-patient-health-minister-idUSKCN20I0M0?il=0|title=Afghanistan confirms first coronavirus case in province bordering Iran|date=24 February 2020|newspaper=Reuters}}</ref>\n\n===March 2020===\n\n==== 1 to 14 March \u2013 Early spread ====\nOn 7 March, three new cases were confirmed in [[Herat Province]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-healthcare-coronavirus-afghanistan-idUSKBN20U085|title=Afghanistan's confirmed coronavirus cases rises to four - health ministry spokesman|date=2020-03-07|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-03-09|language=en}}</ref> The new total of positive cases in Afghanistan had risen to 4.\n\nOn 10 March, the first case was reported outside of Herat province, in [[Samangan Province]], meaning that there was a total of five cases in Afghanistan. The patient had also returned from travels in [[Iran]].<ref name=\"tolonews.com\">{{cite web|url=https://tolonews.com/afghanistan/5-positive-coronavirus-cases-reported-afghanistan|title=5 Positive Coronavirus Cases Reported in Afghanistan|website=TOLOnews|language=en|access-date=2020-03-10}}</ref> This later rose to seven in the evening, as the [[Ministry of Public Health (Afghanistan)|Ministry of Public Health]] announced one new case in both Herat and Samangan provinces.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tolonews.com/afghanistan/7-positive-coronavirus-cases-reported-afghanistan|title=7 Positive Coronavirus Cases Reported in Afghanistan|website=TOLOnews|language=en|access-date=2020-03-10}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 March, the tenth positive case was confirmed. The Ministry of Public Health announced that [[Balkh Province]] and [[Kapisa Province]] had their first cases. Samangan also had their third positive case of coronavirus infection.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite web|url=https://tolonews.com/health/afghanistan-bans-all-sports-events-over-coronavirus-spread|title=Afghanistan Bans All Sports Events Over Coronavirus Spread|website=TOLOnews|language=en|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref> The 23-year-old patient in [[Dawlatabad District]], in northern Balkh, fled Bo Ali Sina Hospital after testing positive.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">{{cite web|url=https://tolonews.com/health/3-more-positive-cases-coronavirus-afghanistan-total-10|title=Update: 11 Tested Positive for Coronavirus In Afghanistan|website=TOLOnews|language=en|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref>\n\nThe eleventh case was also announced that day, as [[Abdul Qayum Rahimi]], the governor of Herat, reported a new positive case of the coronavirus in the province. The total cases in Herat rose to six.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\"/> On 14 March, the first recorded recovery from the coronavirus in Afghanistan was a patient in Herat. Wahid Ahmad, the recovered patient (who was also the first positive case) had contracted COVID-19 from Qom and was hospitalized for two weeks. The first recovered COVID-19 patient in Afghanistan was announced to be in [[quarantine]] at home.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tolonews.com/health/first-recovery-covid-19-afghanistan|title=First Recovery From COVID-19 in Afghanistan|website=TOLOnews|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> The Ministry of Health later revealed on 20 March that three tests he had taken were negative and that he was allowed to end quarantine.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://menafn.com/1099852542/Afghanistan-Herat-discharges-first-recovered-coronavirus-patient|title=Afghanistan- Herat discharges first recovered coronavirus patient|last=MENAFN|website=menafn.com|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://tolonews.com/health/afghan-covid-19-survivor-strong-morale-key|title=Afghan COVID-19 Survivor: 'Strong Morale' is Key|website=TOLOnews|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\n==== 15 to 24 March \u2013 First death ====\nFive new cases were reported on 15 March, which included the first case in [[Daykundi Province]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/afghan-govt-confirms-16-positive-covid19-cases/1761966|title=Afghan govt confirms 16 positive COVID-19 cases|website=outlookindia.com/|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 March, five new positive cases were identified, meaning that the total number of cases rose to 21.<ref name=\":22\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/world/asia/taliban-sound-alarm-over-coronavirus-in-afghanistan-1.993428|title=Taliban sound alarm over coronavirus in Afghanistan|website=The National|language=en|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref> 38 patients, including one positive patient, escaped from quarantine in Herat Province by beating up workers in the hospital and breaking the windows with the help of relatives. All 38 patients were quarantined after returning from Iran.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-afghanistan-idUSKBN2132L3|title=Patients, at least 1 with coronavirus, break out of Afghan quarantine|date=2020-03-16|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-03-17|language=en}}</ref> Also on that day, the [[Taliban]] announced that they had arrested the runaway patient from Dawlatabad District, Balkh Province, and had handed him back to health authorities.<ref name=\":22\"/>\n\nOn 17 March, there were 22 total cases confirmed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/war-ravaged-afghanistan-battles-threat-coronavirus-200316135224827.html|title=War-ravaged Afghanistan battles a new threat: coronavirus|website=www.aljazeera.com|access-date=2020-03-17}}</ref> Also on that day, 7 patients that escaped from Herat Hospital were returned.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tolonews.com/health/7-escaped-patients-returned-herat-hospital|title=7 Escaped Patients Returned to Herat Hospital|website=TOLOnews|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>  By 19 March, two new positive cases were confirmed for the first time in [[Badghis Province|Badghis]] and [[Logar Province|Logar]] provinces.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tolonews.com/index.php/health/nowruz-festival-won%E2%80%99t-be-celebrated-publically-govt|title=Nawroz Festival Won't be Celebrated Publically: Govt|website=TOLOnews|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 March, 10 new cases were reported out of 97 tests, resulting in a total of 34 positive cases. New cases were reported in [[Ghazni Province|Ghazni]], [[Kandahar]] and [[Zabul Province|Zabul]] provinces. The two new cases in [[Kabul Province]] were both foreign diplomats.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://tolonews.com/health/positive-coronavirus-cases-raise-34-afghanistan|title=Positive Coronavirus Cases Raise to 34 in Afghanistan|website=TOLOnews|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> The first possible fatality of COVID-19 in Afghanistan was also announced on 22 March. The male patient was a new suspected case who displayed symptoms. The ministry said that the man visited a hospital in Herat because he was suffering from [[Cardiovascular disease|heart disease]], but after showing signs of COVID-19 he was taken to the coronavirus treatment center in the province. An autopsy will determine whether the Herat man had contracted the coronavirus, or had died of heart disease.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tolonews.com/health/herat-man-covid-19-symptoms-dies|title=Herat Man With COVID-19 Symptoms Dies|website=TOLOnews|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 March, Khalilullah Hekmati, head of Balkh's public health directorate, announced the first official death of an Afghan due to COVID-19. The man died in [[Chimtal District]], in Balkh Province. The test was confirmed positive on 22 March, but the 40-year-old patient had died three days before.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tolonews.com/health/first-coronavirus-death-confirmed-afghanistan|title=First Coronavirus Death Confirmed in Afghanistan|website=TOLOnews|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rferl.org/a/covid-19-north-macedonia-romania-set-curfews-serbia-extends-nighttime-restrictions/30502069.html|title=COVID-19: First Deaths In Afghanistan, Kosovo, Romania, North Macedonia|website=RadioFreeEurope/RadioLiberty|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> By the end of the day, the number of cases increased to 40, after 6 new cases were reported. These included the first two cases in [[Farah Province]] and the first case in [[Ghor Province]]. Three new cases were also reported in Herat. 18 new cases in one day marked the biggest increase of positive cases in a single day.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tolonews.com/health/govt-release-inmates-due-covid-19|title=Govt to Release Inmates Due to COVID-19|website=TOLOnews|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://tolonews.com/health/6-new-covid-19-cases-40-total-afghanistan|title=6 New COVID-19 Cases, 40 Total in Afghanistan|website=TOLOnews|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> On 23 March, two new cases were reported in the provinces of Logar and Samangan.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tolonews.com/health/afghans-not-practicing-social-distancing-health-ministry|title=Afghans not Practicing Social Distancing: Health Ministry|website=TOLOnews|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> On 24 March, 32 new cases were reported, making the total number of cases 74.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tolonews.com/afghanistan/32-new-cases-covid-10-afghanistan-total-74|title=32 New Cases of COVID-10 in Afghanistan, Total 74|website=TOLOnews|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> All of the new cases were reported in Herat.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gandhara.rferl.org/a/health-minister-predicts-majority-of-afghans-will-get-coronavirus/30506935.html|title=Health Minister Predicts Majority Of Afghans Will Get Coronavirus|website=RFE/RL|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\n==== 25 to 31 March \u2013 Outbreak ====\nOn 25 March, 5 new positive cases were reported, as well as the second death in the country. The total climbed up to 79.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.garda.com/crisis24/news-alerts/326366/afghanistan-authorities-confirm-79-covid-19-cases-as-of-march-25-update-2|title=Afghanistan: Authorities confirm 79 COVID-19 cases as of March 25 /update 2|website=GardaWorld|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> The figure later rose to 84 positive cases. The patient who died was a 45-year-old woman in Herat Province. The first case was also announced in [[Nimruz Province]], where the patient had recently traveled to Iran. The second recovery was also reported.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tolonews.com/afghanistan/45-year-old-woman-dies-coronavirus-afghanistan|title=45-Year-Old Woman Dies of Coronavirus in Afghanistan|website=TOLOnews|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://tolonews.com/health/coronavirus-cases-reach-84-officials|title=Coronavirus Cases Reach 84: Officials|website=TOLOnews|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 March, two deaths were announced. The first patient was a 55-year-old who had died at Herat Hospital. The second death in the evening was confirmed to be a man who had returned to Herat from [[London]], [[United Kingdom]]. The total death toll increased to 4.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tolonews.com/afghanistan/health-minister-calls-afghans-take-coronavirus-seriously|title=Health Minister Calls on Afghans to Take Coronavirus Seriously|website=TOLOnews|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> Ten new positive cases were also reported. 8 were located in Herat Province, whilst the two other cases were from Nimruz Province.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tolonews.com/afghanistan/four-deaths-covid-19-local-officials|title=Four Deaths from COVID-19: Local Officials|website=TOLOnews|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 March, 16 new cases were announced by the Ministry of Health. This included 11 new cases in Herat Province, three in Farah Province and one in Ghor Province. The total number of cases reached 110. The third recovery in the country was also reported.<ref name=\"tolonews1\">{{cite web|url=https://tolonews.com/health/coronavirus-cases-reach-110-afghanistan|title=Coronavirus Cases Reach 110 in Afghanistan|website=TOLOnews|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> By 29 March, there was a total of 120 positive cases.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tolonews.com/health/doctors-ask-residents-stay-home-amid-kabul-lockdown|title=Doctors Ask Residents to Stay at Home amid Kabul Lockdown|website=TOLOnews|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> On 30 March, 25 new cases were announced, meaning that the total number of cases increased to 145. The first cases were recorded in [[Badakhshan Province|Badakhshan]], [[Nangarhar Province|Nangarhar]], [[Paktia Province|Paktia]] and [[Sar-e Pol Province|Sar-e Pol]] provinces. Two new recoveries were also reported.<ref name=\"ReferenceD\">{{cite web|url=https://tolonews.com/health/ministry-increases-testing-capacity-covid-19|title=Ministry Increases Testing Capacity for COVID-19|website=TOLOnews|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> On 31 March, the Ministry of Health reported four new cases from 60 tests. Two of the cases were reported in Kandahar, while one new case each was recorded in Daykundi and Nimruz provinces.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tolonews.com/health/confirmed-coronavirus-cases-afghanistan-174|title=Confirmed Coronavirus Cases in Afghanistan: 196|website=TOLOnews|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> 22 other positive cases were later announced as positive with twelve in Herat, six in Kabul, and one new case each in [[Baghlan Province|Baghlan]] (the first in the province), Ghazni and Paktia provinces. By the end of March, the number of positive cases had reached 196.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tolonews.com/health/196-confirmed-covid-19-cases-afghanistan|title=196 Confirmed COVID-19 Cases in Afghanistan|website=TOLOnews|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n=== April 2020 ===\n\n==== 1-9 April ====\nOn 1 April, 43 new cases were announced, including 16 doctors and nurses in Herat and two further cases in the capital, Kabul. The total number of coronavirus cases rose to 239. Health officials reported that over 100 staff members at hospitals in Herat Province are suspected cases.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tolonews.com/health/confirmed-coronavirus-cases-afghanistan-raise-239|title=Confirmed Coronavirus Cases in Afghanistan Raise to 239|website=TOLOnews|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://tolonews.com/health/16-doctors-and-nurses-herat-infected-covid-19|title=16 Doctors and Nurses in Herat Infected with COVID-19|website=TOLOnews|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nOn the morning of 2 April, six new cases were reported. 5 were located in Kabul Province and one was located in Daykundi Province. The total number of cases reached 245.<ref name=\"ReferenceE\">{{cite web|url=https://tolonews.com/health/confirmed-coronavirus-cases-afghanistan-raise-239|title=Confirmed Coronavirus Cases in Afghanistan: 245|website=TOLOnews|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> In the evening, the figure reached 273, after 15 new cases were confirmed in Herat Province, as well as another death. The 13 other new cases were located in Baghlan, Kabul, Kandahar and Paktia provinces.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tolonews.com/health/confirmed-coronavirus-cases-afghanistan-raise-239|title=Confirmed Coronavirus Cases in Afghanistan: 273|website=TOLOnews|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 April, the number of confirmed cases reached 281. 20 new cases were from Herat, 14 in Kabul, and one new case each in the provinces of Ghor, Nangarhar, and Nimroz.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ariananews.af/positive-cases-of-coronavirus-rise-to-281-afghanistan/|title=Positive cases of Coronavirus rise to 281 \u2013 Afghanistan|last=News|first=Ariana|website=Ariana News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> In the evening, the Ministry of Public Health announced 299 total cases. Herat Province had 206 cases, whilst Kabul Province had the second-highest number of cases (43). The cases in Herat Province entail 144 men and 60 women, as well as four fatalities and five recoveries. New cases were also reported in Balkh, Ghazni, Logar, and Samangan provinces. The first cases were recorded in [[Faryab Province|Faryab]] and [[Kunduz Province|Kunduz]] provinces.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tolonews.com/health/coronavirus-cases-299-afghanistan|title=Coronavirus Cases at 299 in Afghanistan|website=TOLOnews|language=en|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref><ref name=\"ReferenceF\">{{cite web|url=https://tolonews.com/index.php/health/300-bed-hospital-opened-covid-19-patients-herat|title=300-Bed Hospital Opened for COVID-19 Patients in Herat|website=TOLOnews|language=en|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 April, the Ministry of Public Health announced that the total had reached 337. The seventh fatality in the country was also reported, whilst two more patients recovered. The 38 new cases were located in 9 provinces. Herat and Kabul had ten new cases each. Kandahar had eight, Paktia had three, Balkh and Samangan had two, whilst Kapisa and Zabul provinces had one new case each. [[Takhar Province]] reported their first case. The cases in Herat Province rose to 216, while in Kabul Province it rose to 53 cases.<ref name=\"ReferenceG\">{{cite web|url=https://tolonews.com/health/coronavirus-cases-rise-337-afghanistan-health-ministry|title=Coronavirus Cases Rise to 337 in Afghanistan: Health Ministry|website=TOLOnews|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 April, the Ministry of Public Health confirmed 30 new cases, which brought the total number of cases to 367. Herat had 16 new cases, Kabul had six, Nimruz had three, Faryab and Kunduz both had two, and Daykundi only had one new case. 5 new recoveries were reported, meaning that the total number of recoveries in Afghanistan reached 17.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tolonews.com/index.php/health/coronavirus-cases-afghanistan-367|title=Coronavirus Cases in Afghanistan: 367|website=TOLOnews|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 April, the death toll increased to 11, as a doctor from a private hospital in Kabul was reported as the eleventh fatality in the country. The Health Ministry also reported the eighteenth recovery. Out of 2737 suspected cases, only 367 had tested positive.<ref name=\"tolonews2\">{{cite web|url=https://tolonews.com/index.php/health/number-covid-19-cases-afghanistan-367|title=Number of COVID-19 Cases in Afghanistan: 367|website=TOLOnews|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> However, in the evening it was reported that 27 new cases in Herat Province were recorded from 140 tests. 21 were men, while 6 were women. Overall, 56 new cases were confirmed positive. Kabul had 12 new cases, Kandahar had 10, Balkh had 5, and Nangarhar had 2 new cases confirmed. The total increased to 423.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tolonews.com/health/56-new-covid-19-cases-afghanistan-total-423|title=56 New COVID-19 Cases in Afghanistan, Total 423|website=TOLOnews|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 April, two new cases were reported in Kandahar Province.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tolonews.com/health/coronavirus-testing-lab-opens-kandahar-officials|title=Coronavirus Testing Lab Opens in Kandahar: Officials|website=TOLOnews|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> On 8 April, the 14th death and 20th recovery were announced. A doctor had died at a clinic in Kabul, which was later closed. The first cases were reported in [[Helmand Province|Helmand]] and [[Maidan Wardak Province|Wardak]] provinces.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tolonews.com/index.php/health/amiri-medical-complex%E2%80%99s-activities-suspended-health-ministry|title=Kabul Clinic Shut Down After Doctor Dies from COVID-19|website=TOLOnews|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> On 9 April, 40 new cases were reported, as well as the 15th fatality, and 32 recoveries. 14 new cases were recorded in Nimruz, ten in Kabul, seven in Kandahar, four in Paktia, two each in Balkh and [[Bamyan Province|Bamyan]] (the first cases in the province), and a single new case in Logar Province.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tolonews.com/health/40-new-covid-19-cases-afghanistan-total-484|title=40 New COVID-19 Cases in Afghanistan, Total 484|website=TOLOnews|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> With 257 cases, four of the 15 Afghan fatalities had been reported in Herat Province. Despite this, no new cases in Herat Province were recorded on 9 April.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tolonews.com/health/herat-residents-ignore-travel-restrictions|title=Herat Residents Ignore Travel Restrictions|website=TOLOnews|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>  The Ministry revealed that the deaths recorded up until 9 April entailed four in Balkh and Herat, three in Kabul, two in Nangarhar, and one each in Daukundi and Takhar provinces.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tolonews.com/health/40-new-covid-19-cases-afghanistan-total-484|title=40 New COVID-19 Cases in Afghanistan, Total 484|website=TOLOnews|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n==== 10-19 April ====\nOn 10 April, 37 new cases were tested positive, including the first case in [[Parwan Province]]. 16 new cases were recorded in Kabul, Herat had eight, whilst Daykundi, Kandahar, Logar, Takhar all had two new cases. The Ministry of Public Health also announced that Bamiyan had a single new case.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tolonews.com/health/covid-19-cases-afghanistan-reach-521|title=COVID-19 Cases in Afghanistan Reach 521|website=TOLOnews|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> By 10 April, at least 20 employees at the [[Arg (Kabul)|Arg (Presidential Palace)]] had contracted COVID-19 in Kabul.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tolonews.com/health/20-palace-have-tested-positive-covid-19-documents|title=20 at Palace Have Tested Positive for COVID-19: Documents|website=TOLOnews|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> \n\nAnother 34 cases were announced by the Ministry of Public Health in the evening. Herat and Kabul both had eight new cases, Kandahar had 5, Nimruz and Wardak had 4, Balkh has two, whilst Badghis, Baghlan, and Ghor all had a single new case each. The total number of cases reached 555, after an increase of 71 new cases, which is the highest number of cases reported in a single day in Afghanistan.\n\nThree new fatalities were also reported, including two men in Kabul. One of the two had spread COVID-19 to 12 other people in their family. The men were 67 and 37 years old.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tolonews.com/health/555-covid-19-cases-afghanistan-18-deaths-reported|title=555 COVID-19 Cases in Afghanistan, 18 Deaths Reported|website=TOLOnews|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 April, 52 new cases were recorded, meaning that the total number of cases reached 607. Kabul had 28 new cases, Kandahar had 8, Herat had 7, Balkh had 4, Bamiyan had 2, whilst Helmand, Nangarhar, and Paktia all had a single new case each.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tolonews.com/health/607-confirmed-coronavirus-cases-afghanistan|title=607 Confirmed Coronavirus Cases in Afghanistan|website=TOLOnews|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\n== Other cases ==\n[[Pakistan]] identified two positive cases at the [[Torkham|Torkham border]], on 12 March. It was reported that one Afghan citizen with coronavirus was returned from [[Torkham, Pakistan|Torkham]] to Afghanistan. The second case at the border was a [[List of diplomatic missions of Pakistan|Pakistani embassy]] employee from [[Kabul]].<ref name=\"ReferenceC\">{{cite web|url=https://tolonews.com/health/how-serious-coronavirus-afghanistan|title=How Serious is the Coronavirus in Afghanistan?|website=TOLOnews|language=en|access-date=2020-03-12}}</ref> On 15 March, Pakistan deported 10 Afghans at Torkham after they developed flu-like symptoms.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/2176465/1-pakistan-depots-10-virus-suspects-native-afghanistan/|title=Pakistan deports 10 virus suspects to native Afghanistan|last=Tribune.com.pk|date=2020-03-15|website=The Express Tribune|language=en|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 March, the [[Resolute Support Mission]] reported that 4 coalition service members had tested positive.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tolonews.com/health/4-coalition-personnel-tested-positive-coronavirus|title=4 Coalition Personnel Tested Positive for Coronavirus|website=TOLOnews|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\nAlso on 24 March, a 51-year-old Afghan national in [[Medina]], [[Saudi Arabia]] was announced as the first casualty from the coronavirus in that country. The Afghan had died on 23 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tolonews.com/health/afghan-national-dies-covid-19-saudi-arabia|title=Afghan National Dies of COVID-19 in Saudi Arabia|website=TOLOnews|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/world/gulf/saudi/coronavirus-saudi-arabia-reports-first-death-205-new-cases-of-covid-19-1.1585054457152|title=Coronavirus: Saudi Arabia reports first death, 205 new cases of COVID-19|website=gulfnews.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\n== Prevention measures ==\n\n=== Testing and health facilities ===\nUp until 10 March, the [[Afghan Government|Afghan government]] had spent $15 million in response to the outbreak and a total of 142 suspected cases had been tested, with only five being positive for COVID-19.<ref name=\"tolonews.com\"/> Tests were sent to [[Netherlands|the Netherlands]] to ensure testing accuracy. Isolation centers were also set up across the country.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-healthcare-coronavirus-afghanistan-idUSKBN20U085|title=Afghanistan's confirmed coronavirus cases rises to four - health ministry spokesman|date=2020-03-07|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-03-10|language=en}}</ref> Up until 14 March, the Afghan government had spent $25 million to tackle the outbreak, which included $7 million of aid packages. A total of 50,000 testing kits had been supplied by the Afghan government.<ref name=\":4\">{{cite web|url=https://tolonews.com/health/govt-will-provide-50k-testing-kits-coronavirus|title=Govt Will Provide 50k Testing Kits for Coronavirus|website=TOLOnews|language=en|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 March, the [[Ministry of Public Health (Afghanistan)|Ministry of Public Health]] had tested 181 suspected cases. The samples of the suspected cases were from [[Herat Province|Herat]], [[Samangan Province|Samangan]], [[Kapisa Province|Kapisa]], [[Balkh Province|Balkh]], [[Daykundi Province|Daykundi]], [[Parwan Province|Parwan]] and [[Paktia Province|Paktia]] provinces.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\" /><ref name=\"ReferenceB\" /> By 18 March, the Ministry of Public Health had registered at least 340 suspected cases of coronavirus in 23 provinces of the country since the start of the outbreak.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=https://tolonews.com/health/moi-puts-ban-public-gatherings-over-coronavirus|title=MoI Puts Ban on Public Gatherings over Coronavirus|website=TOLOnews|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 March, the Ministry of Public Health said that no private labs or hospitals are allowed to undertake the checking of suspected or positive patients. The Ministry of Public Health announced that they intended to increase the capacity of laboratories for testing coronavirus samples in Herat and Balkh provinces. it was announced that a new laboratory in Herat is under construction, after the only laboratory in the country was in [[Kabul]], meaning that it took longer to diagnose people who took tests.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/punishment-muted-nowruz-afghanistan-coronavirus-200320143643578.html|title='God's punishment': Muted Nowruz in Afghanistan over coronavirus|website=www.aljazeera.com|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\nThe Health Ministry later restricted the policy on testing, testing only people with a high fever. It was reported that returnees from Iran had visited the Afghan-Japan Communicable Disease Hospital, which treats COVID-19 patients in Kabul, but were not tested. By 27 March, only 600 tests on returnees from Iran had been carried out.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thediplomat.com/2020/03/how-afghanistan-failed-to-contain-covid-19/|title=How Afghanistan Failed to Contain COVID-19|last=Mehrdad|first=Ezzatullah|website=thediplomat.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> The Ministry reported that in total, over 1000 tests had been carried out by 28 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/asia-pacific/coronavirus-cases-surge-above-100-in-afghanistan/1783114|title=Coronavirus cases surge above 100 in Afghanistan|website=www.aa.com.tr|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://menafn.com/1099927378/Afghanistan-total-coronavirus-cases-increase-to-91|title=Afghanistan total coronavirus cases increase to 91|last=MENAFN|website=menafn.com|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 March, the Minister of Public Health, Ferozuddin Feroz, announced the plan to increase the capacity of health facilities in Afghanistan to 1000 tests a day by the end of the week. A center previously used to treat animals is operating as a testing facility, performing around 100 tests in 24 hours. By the end of March 2020, Afghanistan's COVID-19 testing centers had the capacity of 600 tests a day. 400 of them were in Kabul, 100 in Herat and 100 in Nangarhar.<ref name=\"ReferenceD\"/>\n\nOn 4 April, the Ministry of Public Health opened a testing center in [[Mazar-i-Sharif]], [[Balkh Province]], with the capacity of testing 30 cases a day. The capacity of the center will increase to 200 cases per day within a week.<ref name=\"ReferenceH\">{{cite web|url=https://tolonews.com/index.php/health/covid-19-testing-center-opened-balkh|title=COVID-19 Testing Center Opened in Balkh|website=TOLOnews|language=en|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref> Also on that day, a 300-bed temporary hospital was opened in Herat Province, designated for COVID-19 patients. A local businessman had decided to convert a hotel into a hospital and treatment center for COVID-19 patients. The new hospital is the second center for COVID-19 patients in the province and the capacity of the new hospital will increase to 1000 beds, if needed. Suspected cases in Herat Province will also be admitted to the hospital. Around 200 doctors and nurses were hired at the hospital and received training on the COVID-19 treatment.<ref name=\"ReferenceF\"/>\n\nOn 7 April, a testing facility in Kandahar opened, which also caters for the provinces of [[Helmand Province|Helmand]], [[Urozgan Province|Urozgan]], and [[Zabul Province|Zabul]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tolonews.com/index.php/health/coronavirus-testing-lab-opens-kandahar-officials|title=Coronavirus Testing Lab Opens in Kandahar: Officials|website=TOLOnews|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n=== Lockdown measures ===\nOn 14 March, [[President of Afghanistan|President]] [[Ashraf Ghani]], told the public to avoid large public gatherings and to pay attention to hygiene to prevent the spread of the disease.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\" /> On 18 March, the [[Ministry of Interior Affairs (Afghanistan)|Ministry of Interior Affairs]] banned all large gatherings, including the closure of venues that attract large crowds such as entertainment places, sports grounds, swimming pools, fitness clubs and wedding halls.\n\nOn 22 March, Public Health Minister [[Ferozuddin Feroz]] urged the government to order the lockdown of the city of [[Herat]] at a press conference in Kabul.<ref name=\":0\" /> Members of the [[House of the People (Afghanistan)|Wolesi Jirga]] of [[National Assembly (Afghanistan)|Afghanistan's parliament]] decided to hold a general session once a week to avoid the spread of COVID-19.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tolonews.com/health/wolesi-jirga-meet-less-amid-coronavirus|title=Wolesi Jirga to Meet Less Amid Coronavirus|website=TOLOnews|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> The spokesperson of the Health Ministry, Wahidullah Mayar, announced that 449 suspected cases had been tested across 28 provinces up until 22 March. Most suspected cases were from Herat and Kabul.<ref>{{Citation|title=MEHWAR: 449 Suspected Coronavirus Cases Tested {{!}} TOLOnews|url=https://tolonews.com/mehwar/mehwar-449-suspected-coronavirus-cases-tested|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 March, in [[Jalalabad]], [[Nangarhar Province]], the local authorities placed strict measures in the provincial capital, limiting the movement of citizens until 1 April.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.urdupoint.com/en/world/afghan-authorities-close-eastern-city-of-jala-873131.html|title=Afghan Authorities Close Eastern City Of Jalalabad Due To Coronavirus Fears - Spokesman|website=UrduPoint|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-890tkPGjJE |title=Afghanistan: Vendors in Jalalabad more afraid of poverty than coronavirus amid city lockdown |publisher=YouTube |date=2020-03-25 |accessdate=2020-03-30}}</ref> On 25 March, the Afghan Government began to limit the movement of residents in [[Farah Province|Farah]], Herat and [[Nimruz Province|Nimruz]] provinces, after Herat emerged as a major source of internal transmissions in Afghanistan. In Herat, praying in [[mosque]]s was suspended to prevent any possible spread of the virus. Residents of [[Farah, Afghanistan|Farah]] and [[Zaranj]] could only go out for necessary activities.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tolonews.com/index.php/health/covid-19-govt-limits-residents-movement-herat|title=COVID-19: Govt Limits Residents' Movement in Herat|website=TOLOnews|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/coronavirus-herat-emerges-afghanistan-epicentre-200325032420910.html|title=Coronavirus: Herat emerges as Afghanistan's epicentre|website=www.aljazeera.com|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://gandhara.rferl.org/a/afghanistan-locks-down-gateway-city-of-coronavirus-outbreak/30509289.html|title=Afghanistan Locks Down 'Gateway' City Of Coronavirus Outbreak|website=RFE/RL|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 March, the government announced the release of 10,000 prisoners that were aged over 55 to slow the spread of COVID-19 in the country. This also consisted of mainly women, youths and the critically ill.<ref>[https://news.yahoo.com/afghanistan-release-10-000-prisoners-slow-coronavirus-spread-211850224.html Afghanistan to release up to 10,000 prisoners to slow coronavirus spread] AFP, 26 Mar 2020</ref> Based on President Ashraf Ghani's decree, the prisoners would be released over the 10 following days. The release of prisoners did not include members of [[Islamic terrorism|Islamist militant groups]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tolonews.com/afghanistan/govt-release-thousands-prisoners-amid-covid-19|title=Govt to Release Thousands of Prisoners Amid COVID-19|website=TOLOnews|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-health-coronavirus-afghanistan-prison-idUKKBN21D32E|title=Afghanistan to release 10,000 prisoners to slow spread of coronavirus|date=2020-03-26|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-03-27|language=en}}</ref> Also on that day, Afghan authorities extended the lockdown to [[Kabul Province|Kabul]], [[Kandahar Province|Kandahar]], and [[Logar Province|Logar]] provinces.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gandhara.rferl.org/a/to-stop-coronavirus-spread-afghanistan-to-release-thousands-of-inmates/30511258.html|title=In Bid To Stop Coronavirus Spread, Afghanistan To Release Thousands of Inmates|website=RFE/RL|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> Also on 26 March, the mayor of Mazar-i-Sharif said that in addition to closing restaurants in the city, [[Disinfectant|disinfection]] of public places is also taking place.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tolonews.com/fa/health/%D8%AB%D8%A8%D8%AA-%DB%B9-%D8%B1%D9%88%DB%8C%D8%AF%D8%A7%D8%AF-%D9%85%D8%B4%DA%A9%D9%88%DA%A9-%D9%88%DB%8C%D8%B1%D9%88%D8%B3-%DA%A9%D8%B1%D9%88%D9%86%D8%A7-%D8%AF%D8%B1-%D8%A8%D9%84%D8%AE|title=\u062b\u0628\u062a \u06f9 \u0631\u0648\u06cc\u062f\u0627\u062f \u0645\u0634\u06a9\u0648\u06a9 \u0648\u06cc\u0631\u0648\u0633 \u06a9\u0631\u0648\u0646\u0627 \u062f\u0631 \u0628\u0644\u062e|website=\u0637\u0644\u0648\u0639\u200c\u0646\u06cc\u0648\u0632|language=fa|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 March, it was announced that the Afghan cabinet had decided that the capital of Afghanistan, [[Kabul]], would undergo lockdown from 28 March for three weeks. The lockdown will ensure that residents stay at home, avoiding all non-essential travel and gatherings. Residents would also need to provide valid reasons if they decide to leave their homes. All restaurants, hotels, sauna, cafes, public bathing centers, shrines, gyms, parks and other stores will remain closed for 3 weeks, except for grocery stores and banks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gandhara.rferl.org/a/afghanistan-locks-down-capital-to-avoid-coronavirus-tide/30513293.html|title=Afghanistan Locks Down Capital To Avoid Coronavirus Tide|website=RFE/RL|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> It was also announced that all sport venues, shrines and other public gathering places would remain closed for the duration of lockdown in Kabul.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tolonews.com/index.php/health/kabul-lockdown-begins-saturday-officials|title=Kabul Lockdown Begins Saturday: Officials|website=TOLOnews|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> Public transport carrying more than 5 passengers will also be banned. Large educational institutes and wedding halls will be transformed into isolation centers to [[quarantine]] those who return from [[Iran]] for two weeks. A total of 70 military teams will patrol Kabul to identify people with symptoms.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.devdiscourse.com/article/headlines/979933-coronavirus-afghanistan-approves-plan-to-impose-lockdown-in-kabul|title=Coronavirus: Afghanistan approves plan to impose lockdown in Kabul|website=Devdiscourse|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 April, officials from [[Balkh Province]] reported that [[Mazar-i-Sharif]] is under partial lockdown as public places were closed.<ref name=\"ReferenceH\"/>\n\n=== International funding and aid ===\nOn 14 March, [[Beijing]] ([[China]]) announced that they would give aid to [[Afghanistan]]. The [[World Bank]], [[Asian Development Bank]] and [[World Health Organization]] also announced that they would provide help.<ref name=\":4\" /> The Chinese medical aid arrived on 2 April, after aid from the [[United Arab Emirates]] was received on the previous day. It was also announced on that day that [[Uzbekistan]] would provide aid for Afghanistan.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tolonews.com/health/chinas-medical-supply-shipment-arrives-kabul|title=China's Medical Supply Shipment Arrives in Kabul|website=TOLOnews|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref><ref name=\"ReferenceE\"/>\n\nOn 21 March, Afghanistan contributed $1 million to the [[South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation]] (SAARC) [[SAARC COVID-19 Emergency Fund|emergency fund]] to help fight COVID-19.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://theprint.in/diplomacy/after-nepal-bhutan-now-afghanistan-maldives-pledge-support-to-saarc-covid-19-fund/385455/|title=SAARC|last=|first=|date=21 March 2020|website=www.theprint.in|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 April, the World Bank approved $100.4 million of aid to help Afghanistan.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tolonews.com/health/world-bank-approves-100m-aid-afghanistan|title=World Bank Approves $100M in Aid for Afghanistan|website=TOLOnews|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n=== Public awareness ===\nOn 22 March, doctors at Blossom Hospital in Kabul launched a public awareness campaign to help the public understand how to prevent the spread of the virus. This included distributing over 5000 [[surgical mask]]s to the public.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nOn 23 March, [[Cordaid]] announced that they would distribute soap in communities, handle waste management and supply thermometers to reduce the risk of spread in Afghanistan. They also held community awareness sessions and helped to improve the referral systems of patients to health centers that have a treatment ward for COVID-19.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://reliefweb.int/report/afghanistan/countering-covid-19-afghanistan-let-be-wake-call|title=Countering COVID-19 in Afghanistan. \"Let this be a wake-up call\" - Afghanistan|website=ReliefWeb|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\nClerics and religious scholars enforced a [[fatwa]] on 5 April.<ref name=\"tolonews3\">{{cite web|url=https://tolonews.com/health/afghan-clerics-ban-religious-political-gatherings-amid-covid-19|title=Afghan Clerics Ban Religious, Political Gatherings Amid COVID-19|website=TOLOnews|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> It was reported on 6 April, that many [[Volunteering|volunteer groups]] and [[Community health worker|community health workers]] had begun awareness campaigns, such as a door-to-door campaign by a group of women in [[Parwan Province]] and a provincial campaign for [[Faryab Province]] by local officials. The Ministry of Public Health also began to spread awareness via [[social media]] and [[Old media|traditional media]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tolonews.com/health/house-visits-raise-afghan-covid-19-awareness|title=House Visits Raise Afghan COVID-19 Awareness|website=TOLOnews|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n=== Taliban's cooperation ===\nOn 16 March, the [[Taliban]] announced that in [[Balkh|Balkh Province]], they arrested the runaway patient who tested positive for coronavirus and handed him back to health authorities. The Taliban also spread awareness of the coronavirus in insurgent-controlled areas of Afghanistan and supported governmental health workers. They also asked for Afghan returnees from Iran to be tested for COVID-19.<ref name=\":22\"/> \n\nOn 27 March, the Taliban started a public awareness campaign in [[Jowzjan Province]]. On 29 March, the Taliban launched a COVID-19 public awareness campaign in [[Logar Province]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tolonews.com/index.php/health/taliban-launches-awareness-campaign-coronavirus|title=Taliban Launches Awareness Campaign on Coronavirus|website=TOLOnews|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> The Taliban offered safe passage to health workers that are treating coronavirus patients in Afghanistan. Furthermore, the Taliban enforced lockdowns in affected districts. People who were suspected of having COVID-19 were quarantined.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/04/taliban-launches-campaign-afghanistan-fight-coronavirus-200406055113086.html|title=Taliban launches campaign to help Afghanistan fight coronavirus|website=www.aljazeera.com|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n=== Mask production ===\nOn 26 February, a mask-production plant in [[Herat Province]] (the epicenter of the outbreak in Afghanistan) opened. The plant produces over 60,000 masks on a daily basis. The [[Ministry of Public Health (Afghanistan)|Ministry of Public Health]] announced that this would be important in slowing the spread of [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] and would also help decrease the surge in prices for [[surgical mask]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tolonews.com/business/rapid-mask-production-begins-herat-factory|title=Rapid Mask-Production Begins in Herat Factory|website=TOLOnews|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\n== Impacts ==\n\n=== Cultural events and religion ===\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on religion}}\nThe annual [[Nowruz]] festival in [[Mazar-i-Sharif]] and across the whole of Afghanistan was not held in 2020, in order to prevent the spread of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|global coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/asia-pacific/coronavirus-afghanistan-scraps-annual-nevruz-festival/1763830|title=Coronavirus: Afghanistan scraps annual Nevruz festival|website=www.aa.com.tr|access-date=2020-03-12}}</ref><ref name=\"ReferenceC\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://tolonews.com/index.php/health/nowruz-festival-won%E2%80%99t-be-celebrated-publically-govt|title=Nawroz Festival Won't be Celebrated Publically: Govt|website=TOLOnews|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> The Nowruz celebrations in [[Balkh]] were canceled after the first case was reported on 14 March.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\"/> People were also not allowed to enter the [[Blue Mosque (Mazar-i-Sharif)|Shrine of Hazrat Ali]] in Mazar-i-Sharif.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tolonews.com/fa/afghanistan/%D9%85%D8%B1%D8%A7%D8%B3%D9%85-%D8%AC%D9%87%D9%86%D8%AF%D9%87-%D8%A8%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A7-%D8%AF%D8%B1-%D9%85%D8%B2%D8%A7%D8%B1%D8%B4%D8%B1%DB%8C%D9%81-%D8%B4%D8%A8%E2%80%8C%D9%87%D9%86%DA%AF%D8%A7%D9%85-%D8%A8%D8%B1%DA%AF%D8%B2%D8%A7%D8%B1-%D8%B4%D8%AF|title=\u0645\u0631\u0627\u0633\u0645 \u062c\u0647\u0646\u062f\u0647 \u0628\u0627\u0644\u0627 \u062f\u0631 \u0645\u0632\u0627\u0631\u0634\u0631\u06cc\u0641 \u0634\u0628\u200c\u0647\u0646\u06af\u0627\u0645 \u0628\u0631\u06af\u0632\u0627\u0631 \u0634\u062f|website=\u0637\u0644\u0648\u0639\u200c\u0646\u06cc\u0648\u0632|language=fa|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\nAround 500 mosques were closed in Herat in late March 2020. On 5 April, the [[Ministry of Hajj and Religious Affairs]] and clerics announced a [[fatwa]], including restrictions on [[Friday prayer]]s and other prayers in mosques across Afghanistan.<ref name=\"tolonews3\"/>\n\n=== Sports ===\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on sports}}\nThe [[Afghanistan National Olympic Committee]] (ANOC) announced that all sport events were canceled after 14 March, including a [[Buzkashi]] league tournament that was being held in [[Kabul]].<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\n=== Education ===\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on education}}\nIt was announced on 14 March, that all educational institutes in the country would not open until 21 April.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/asia-pacific/coronavirus-afghanistan-closes-educational-institutions/1766132|title=Coronavirus: Afghanistan closes educational institutions|website=www.aa.com.tr|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref>\n\n=== Social ===\nOn 21 March, wedding halls and [[Turkish bath|hammams]] were closed and governmental departments with large numbers of employees stopped working.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nThe three week lockdown in the capital, [[Kabul]], affected small businesses, such as local shop owners.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tolonews.com/health/lockdown-affects-businesses-kabul|title=Lockdown Affects Businesses in Kabul|website=TOLOnews|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n=== Immigration ===\nDuring March 2020, 30,000 [[Afghans in Iran|Afghan immigrants]] were reported to have returned from [[Iran]], via [[Islam Qala|Islam Qala port]], after the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Iran|outbreak in the country]]. This marked the highest rate of returning immigrants from Iran in over a decade.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tolonews.com/afghanistan/30k-afghans-returned-iran-3-days|title=30K Afghans Returned from Iran in 3 Days|website=TOLOnews|language=en|access-date=2020-03-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://tolonews.com/afghanistan/thousands-afghans-return-iran-amid-coronavirus|title=Thousands of Afghans Return from Iran Amid Coronavirus|website=TOLOnews|language=en|access-date=2020-03-12}}</ref>\n\n=== Effects on travel ===\n\n==== Travel restrictions ====\n{{Main|Travel restrictions related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\nAfter the three suspected cases in [[Herat]], [[Afghanistan]] later temporarily closed its border with [[Iran]] on 23 February 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.france24.com/en/20200223-iran-neighbours-close-their-borders-as-coronavirus-toll-rises|title=Iran neighbours close their borders as coronavirus toll rises|date=2020-02-23|website=France 24|language=en|access-date=2020-03-10}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, the Afghan [[National aviation authority|Civil Aviation Authority]] restricted most international flights by Afghan airlines due to the global pandemic. [[Ariana Afghan Airlines]] and [[Kam Air]] suspended all flights, except from flights to [[Dubai]] and [[Pakistan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tolonews.com/business/afghan-airlines-intl-flights-90-halted-acaa|title=Afghan Airlines Intl Flights 90% Halted: ACAA|website=TOLOnews|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> On 1 April, the [[Government of Afghanistan]] suspended flights between [[Kabul]] and [[Herat]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://caravanmagazine.in/health/indians-in-afghanistan-seek-evacuation|title=COVID-19: Indians in Afghanistan seek to be evacuated, doctors stress lack of PPE|last=Sharma|first=Ashutosh|website=The Caravan|language=en|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\n==== Pakistan's response ====\nIn response to Afghanistan's and [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Iran|Iran's]] cases, [[Pakistan]] closed [[Wesh\u2013Chaman border crossing|its border]] at [[Chaman]] with Afghanistan for at least three weeks, starting on 2 March, as both countries confirmed rising number of cases over the weeks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dunyanews.tv/en/Pakistan/535901-Coronavirus-Pak-Afghan-border-remain-closed-another-week|title=Coronavirus: Pak-Afghan border to remain closed for another week|website=Dunya News|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geo.tv/latest/276370-pakistan-extends-border-closure-with-afghanistan-for-one-more-week|title=Coronavirus: Pakistan extends border closure with Afghanistan for seven days|website=www.geo.tv|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.news18.com/news/world/coronavirus-cases-rise-to-19-in-pakistan-2532501.html|title=Coronavirus Cases Rise to 19 in Pakistan, Partial Closure of Border with Afghanistan to be Extended|date=2020-03-11|website=News18|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref> On 13 March, all land borders with Pakistan were closed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nationalpost.com/pmn/health-pmn/pakistan-to-shut-borders-limit-international-flights-over-coronavirus-minister|title=Pakistan to shut borders, limit international flights over coronavirus -minister {{!}} National Post|last=Health|first=P. M. N.|date=2020-03-13|language=en-CA|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref> It was also announced that Pakistan would completely seal its [[Durand Line|land border with Afghanistan]] from 16 March for at least two weeks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geo.tv/latest/277163-pakistan-set-to-seal-border-with-afghanistan-iran-to-prevent-coronavirus-spread|title=Pakistan set to seal border with Afghanistan, Iran to prevent coronavirus spread|website=www.geo.tv|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref> On 21 March, Pakistan reopened its border with Afghanistan.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geo.tv/latest/278438-pakistan-opens-border-with-afghanistan-despite-coronavirus-fears|title=Pakistan opens border with Afghanistan to allow essential goods to pass through|website=www.geo.tv|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref> \n\nOn 4 April, Pakistan announced that the Chaman and [[Torkham]] borders will open between 6 and 9 April for stranded Afghans to return to their country at the request of the Afghan Government.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/asia-pacific/covid-19-pakistan-to-open-border-for-stranded-afghans/1792507|title=COVID-19: Pakistan to open border for stranded Afghans|website=www.aa.com.tr|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://arynews.tv/en/afghan-nationals-exit-allowed-torkham-border/|title=Pakistan allows exit of Afghan nationals through Torkham|date=2020-04-04|website=ARY NEWS|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://dnd.com.pk/pakistan-allows-afghan-nationals-to-return-to-their-country/185610|title=Pakistan allows Afghan nationals to return to their Country|last=Mati|date=2020-04-04|website=Dispatch News Desk|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://tolonews.com/afghanistan/pakistan-allows-afghans-return-home-kabul%E2%80%99s-request|title=Pakistan Allows Afghans to Return Home at Kabul\u2019s Request|website=TOLOnews|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n==Statistics==\n\n=== Overview ===\nThe table below shows the confirmed COVID-19 cases in each [[Provinces of Afghanistan|Province of Afghanistan]]. As of 12 April 2020, 26 provinces have at least one confirmed positive case of [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]].\n\n[[File:Afghanistan 2020 COVID-19 Map (Allio-19).png|alt=|left|thumb|Map of provinces with confirmed cases of COVID-19 in Afghanistan '''as of 7 April 2020'''. {{legend|#c80000|Confirmed cases reported}}{{legend|#558eed|Suspected cases reported}}]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:500px;\"\n! colspan = \"6\" |COVID-19 in Afghanistan by Province as of 11 April 2020<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tolonews.com/health/40-new-covid-19-cases-afghanistan-total-484|title=40 New COVID-19 Cases in Afghanistan, Total 484|website=TOLOnews|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n|- style=\"background: #efefef;\"\n! Province\n! Cases\n! Deaths\n! Recoveries\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[Badakhshan Province]]\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" | 1\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" | 0\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" | 0\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[Badghis Province]]\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" | 1\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" | 0\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" | 0\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[Baghlan Province]]\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" | 1{{Efn|Only 463 cases are show. 19 cases from 8 April 2020 are not shown from Kabul, Ghazni, Baghlan, Logar, Wardak, Helmand and Takhar.<ref>https://tolonews.com/health/amiri-medical-complex%E2%80%99s-activities-suspended-health-ministry</ref>|name=|group=}}\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" | 0\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" | 0\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[Balkh Province]]\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" | 13\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" | 4\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" | 1<ref name=\"R