{"title_page": "Erik Bakich", "text_new": "{{short description|American college baseball coach|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox college coach\n| name = Erik Bakich\n| image = \n| image_upright = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| current_title = [[Head coach]]\n| current_team = [[Michigan Wolverines baseball|Michigan]]\n| current_conference = [[Big Ten Conference|Big Ten]]\n| current_record = 267\u2013168\n| contract = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1977|11|27}}\n| birth_place = [[San Jose, California]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| alma_mater = [[East Carolina University]]\n| player_years1 = 1997\u20131998\n| player_team1 = [[San Jose City College|San Jose CC]]\n| player_years2 = 1999\u20132000\n| player_team2 = [[East Carolina Pirates baseball|East Carolina]]\n| player_positions = [[Left fielder]]\n| coach_years1 = 2002\n| coach_team1 = [[Clemson Tigers baseball|Clemson]] (assistant)\n| coach_years2 = 2003\u20132009\n| coach_team2 = [[Vanderbilt Commodores baseball|Vanderbilt]] (assistant)\n| coach_years3 = 2010\u20132012\n| coach_team3 = [[Maryland Terrapins baseball|Maryland]]\n| coach_years4 = 2013\u2013present\n| coach_team4 = [[Michigan Wolverines baseball|Michigan]]\n| overall_record = 337\u2013266\n| bowl_record = \n| tournament_record = Big Ten: 10\u20138<br>NCAA: 11\u20138\n| championships = [[2015 Big Ten Conference Baseball Tournament|Big Ten Tournament]] (2015)\n| awards = \nAll-[[Colonial Athletic Association]] (2000)<br>\n[[National Collegiate Baseball Writers Association#National Coach of the Year|NCBWA National Coach of the Year]] (2019)<br>\nD1Baseball Coach of the Year (2019)<br>\n[[Skip Bertman Award|Skip Bertman Coach of the Year]] (2019)<br>\n| coaching_records = \n}}\n\n'''Erik Michael Bakich''' (born November 27, 1977) is an American [[baseball]] coach and former [[left fielder]]. He is the current head baseball coach of the [[Michigan Wolverines baseball|Michigan Wolverines]]. Bakich played [[college baseball]] at [[San Jose City College]] (1997\u20131998) and [[East Carolina University]] for head coach [[Keith LeClair]] from 1999 to 2000. He then served as the head coach of [[Maryland Terrapins baseball|Maryland Terrapins]] (2010\u20132012).\n\n==Early life==\nBakich attended Bellarmine College Preparatory, graduating in 1996. Bakich played [[East Carolina Pirates baseball|baseball]] at [[East Carolina University]] in 1999 and 2000. He played as a [[left fielder]] with a 1.000 [[fielding percentage]] with 91 [[putout]]s, .315 [[Batting average (baseball)|batting average]], 14 [[home run]]s, 85 [[run batted in|RBI]]s, and 87 [[run (baseball)|run]]s. Both years, the Pirates secured the [[Colonial Athletic Association]] championship and earned No. 1 seeds in the NCAA Regionals. Bakich was awarded all-conference honors in 2000.<ref name=hired>[http://www.wdnweb.com/articles/2009/07/01/sports/doc4a4ad7e9b9dab631426688.txt Bakich hired as Terps\u2019 head baseball coach], ''Washington Daily News'', July 1, 2009, retrieved May 29, 2010.</ref> Bakich graduated from East Carolina with a [[sports science]] degree in 2000.<ref name=vbio/>\n\nBakich played independent league baseball, first with the [[Springfield Capitals]] of the [[Frontier League]] in 2000, then in 2001 with the [[Greenville Bluesmen]] of the [[Texas\u2013Louisiana League]], [[Ohio Valley Redcoats|Dubois County Dragons]] of the Frontier League, and the Tennessee T's of the [[All-American Association]].<ref name=bbr>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/register/player.fcgi?id=bakich001eri|title=Erik Bakich|publisher=baseball-reference|accessdate=October 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Coaching career==\nAfter his brief professional playing stint, Bakich embarked upon his coaching career as a volunteer assistant at [[Clemson University]] in 2002. He worked as a hitting coach, and with both infielders and outfielders. Clemson advanced to the [[College World Series]] that season.<ref name=vbio>[http://vucommodores.cstv.com/sports/m-basebl/mtt/bakich_erik00.html Player Bio: Erik Bakich], Vanderbilt University, retrieved May 29, 2010.</ref>\n\nBakich then moved to [[Vanderbilt University]] in 2003 to become the school's recruiting coordinator, [[Coach (baseball)|hitting coach]], and [[Coach (baseball)|outfield instructor]]. ''[[Collegiate Baseball Newspaper|Collegiate Baseball]]'' ranked Bakich's first recruiting class the 24th best in the nation. In 2004, Vanderbilt increased its batting average from .258 the previous season to .304, the largest jump in school history.<ref name=vbio/> Vanderbilt brought in the No. 1 ranked recruiting class in 2005. ''[[Baseball America]]'' ranked the 2006 recruiting class 25th, and the 2007 class 12th. In 2008, the Commodores secured the No. 2 class.<ref name=vbio/> Each year of Bakich's seven-year tenure saw a top-25 ranked recruiting class.<ref name=hired/>\n\n===Maryland===\nIn June 2009, the [[University of Maryland, College Park|University of Maryland]] hired Bakich to replace former nine-year head coach [[Terry Rupp]].<ref name=hired/> Bakich sought to rebuild [[Maryland Terrapins baseball|the program]] and eventually achieve regular appearances in the [[NCAA Division I Baseball Championship|NCAA tournament]], an event Maryland had not qualified for since [[1971 NCAA Division I Baseball Tournament|1971]]. His long-term strategy focused on recruiting, player development, and improving facilities. By September, Bakich had secured eleven commitments in the 2010 recruiting class and one in the 2011 class. He stated his plan to build a \"recruiting wall\" around the state to keep local talent at home. Bakich said, \"Patience is not a virtue of mine. We don't have any time for that shit.\"<ref name=aggressive>[http://www.diamondbackonline.com/sports/an-aggressive-approach-1.474436 An aggressive approach; New baseball coach Erik Bakich is trying to take the Terps' program to new heights], ''[[The Diamondback]]'', September 14, 2009.</ref>\n\nMaryland finished its first season under Bakich with a 17\u201339 mark and 5\u201325 in the [[Atlantic Coast Conference]] (ACC).<ref>[http://www.umterps.com/sports/m-basebl/recaps/052210aaa.html Terps Drop Finale To Wake Forest, 8\u20137; Pinch-hit double in the ninth gives Wake walk-off win], University of Maryland, May 22, 2010.</ref> The Terrapins matched the worst finish in program history. Bakich said, \"I know it sounds odd, but wins and losses have never been important to me. I wanted to change the attitude of this team first and foremost, and you can already see that happening. Our seniors have done a great job of leading this team, and the transformation has already been made.\" The 2011 recruiting class was described as one of the best in school history.<ref>[http://www.diamondbackonline.com/sports/terrapin-baseball-season-in-review-1.1478132 TERRAPIN BASEBALL SEASON IN REVIEW; New coach, same results \u2014 for now], ''The Diamondback'', May 11, 2010.</ref> Bakich resigned as Maryland's head baseball coach on June 27, 2012, in order to pursue his new head coaching career for the [[Michigan Wolverines baseball]] team.\n\n===Michigan===\nOn June 27, 2012, Bakich was named the 19th coach in the history of [[Michigan Wolverines baseball]]. On the same day of Bakich's hire, Bakich made his first public press conference as head coach of [[Michigan Wolverines baseball|Michigan]]. Bakich was most noted for his quote, \"We want to catch that softball program\" meaning Michigan's softball program, and showed great praise for head [[Michigan Wolverines softball|Michigan Softball]] coach [[Carol Hutchins]]. Erik Bakich made many assurances that Michigan baseball will be back to winning championships at a consistent rate, not just every once in a while. Bakich also talked a lot about pitching and defense for Michigan, and bringing in the best recruits locally, regionally, and nationally.<ref>[http://www.freep.com/article/20120628/SPORTS06/120628079/michigan-wolverines-baseball-erik-bakich?odyssey=tab%7Ctopnews%7Ctext%7CSports Snyder, Mark. \"New Michigan baseball coach Erik Bakich: 'We want to catch that softball program'\". Detroit Free Press, 2012, p. 1.]</ref>\n\nOn May 24, 2015, Michigan defeated [[Maryland Terrapins baseball|Maryland]] 4\u20133 in the [[2015 Big Ten Conference Baseball Tournament|Big Ten Conference Tournament]] championship game, securing a bid to the [[2015 NCAA Division I Baseball Tournament|NCAA Tournament]] for the first time since 2008. During the [[2019 Michigan Wolverines baseball team|2019]] season, Bakich led the Wolverines to a 50\u201322 record, including a 16\u20137 Big Ten Conference record, as they advanced to the [[College World Series]] for the first time since [[1984 NCAA Division I Baseball Tournament|1984]]. On June 15, 2019, Bakich was named the [[National Collegiate Baseball Writers Association#National Coach of the Year|NCBWA National Coach of the Year]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://mgoblue.com/news/2019/6/15/baseball-bakich-named-ncbwa-national-coach-of-the-year.aspx |title=Bakich Named NCBWA National Coach of the Year |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |website=MGoBlue.com |first=Kurt |last=Svoboda |date=June 15, 2019 |accessdate=June 15, 2019}}</ref> Later that year, Bakich received the 2019 [[Skip Bertman Award]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Bakich wins 2019 Skip Bertman National Coach of the Year Award |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/bakich-wins-2019-skip-bertman-national-coach-of-the-year-award |website=MLB |accessdate=11 April 2020 |date=September 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Head coaching record==\nBelow is a table of Bakich's yearly records as an NCAA head baseball coach.<ref name=standings2010>{{cite web|title=2010 Atlantic Coast Conference Baseball Standings |url=http://www.d1baseball.com/2010/conferences/standings_acc.htm |work=D1Baseball.com |accessdate=11 June 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68KnQOdJm?url=http://www.d1baseball.com/2010/conferences/standings_acc.htm |archivedate=2012-06-11 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref><ref name=standings2011>{{cite web|title=2011 Atlantic Coast Conference Baseball Standings |url=http://www.d1baseball.com/2011/conferences/standings_acc.htm |work=D1Baseball.com |accessdate=11 June 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68KnS5n28?url=http://www.d1baseball.com/2011/conferences/standings_acc.htm |archivedate=2012-06-11 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref><ref name=standings2012>{{cite web|title=2012 Atlantic Coast Conference Baseball Standings |url=http://www.d1baseball.com/conferences/standings_acc.htm |work=D1Baseball.com |accessdate=11 June 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68KnXQBzp?url=http://www.d1baseball.com/conferences/standings_acc.htm |archivedate=2012-06-11 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref><ref name=bigtenst13>{{cite web|title=2013 Big Ten Conference Baseball Standings |url=http://www.d1baseball.com/conferences/standings_big10.htm |work=D1Baseball.com |publisher=Jeremy Mills |accessdate=May 28, 2013 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6GwbyOViZ?url=http://www.d1baseball.com/conferences/standings_big10.htm |archivedate=May 28, 2013 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref>\n\n{{CBB Yearly Record Start | type = team | conference = | postseason = | poll = both}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Subhead \n| name = [[Maryland Terrapins baseball|Maryland Terrapins]] \n| conference = [[Atlantic Coast Conference]]\n| startyear = 2010\n| endyear = 2012\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Entry \n| championship = \n| season = [[2010 NCAA Division I baseball season|2010]]\n| name = Maryland\n| overall = 17\u201339 \n| conference = 5\u201325 \n| confstanding = 6th <small>(Atlantic)</small>\n | postseason = \n| ranking = no\n| ranking2 = no\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Entry \n|championship = \n| season = [[2011 NCAA Division I baseball season|2011]]\n| name = Maryland\n| overall = 21\u201335 \n| conference = 5\u201325 \n| confstanding = 6th <small>(Atlantic)</small> \n| postseason = \n| ranking = no\n| ranking2 = no\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship =